name: F D
text:
Derni√®re visite au resto, une horreur ! Je prends un petit-d√©jeuner et au pr√©alable j'avais vu sa composition. D√©j√† on m'apporte une bouteille d'eau avec un bouchon mal en point. Je fais la remarque et la serveuse √©tait so√ªl√©e de revenir sur ses pas pour me chercher une autre bouteille. √Ä mon arriv√©e pas d'acceuil chaleureux et l'une des serveuses n'avait d'yeux que pour son t√©l√©phone derri√®re le bar...

On me ram√®ne pas de beurre, pas de venoisseries sans explications. Je me l√®ve pour comprendre on me dit "on peut vous ramenez du beurre" non ! C'est pas comme je veux, c'est compris dans la formule... Et pour les venoisseries, on me dit que pendant le Ramadan y en a pas. Explication pas claire du tout. Je fais remarquer √† la serveuse son comportement pas pro, z√©ro communication avec le client, je lui parle et elle a un l'air limite d√©sinvolte, le ton monte un peu.

Je suis en terrasse et c'√©tait horrible. Trop de mouches et de moustiques et aucune disposition du resto pour am√©liorer mon confort. J'ai fait expr√®s de ne rien dire et ben mon confort n'√©tait pas leur probl√®me.

On me ram√®ne une omelette, un gateau √† l'orange (j'avais pas demand√© ce g√¢teau en plus), avec du miel et du lab√© pas compris dans la formule mais pareil z√©ro explication. La salade de fruit n'√©tait pas fra√Æche, les fruits √©taient un peu d√©fra√Æchis et beaucoup d'eau se trouvaient au fond de la coupole

Au moment de payer grosse d√©ception de la g√©rante avec qui j'ai eu √† √©changer plusieurs fois pour mes pr√©c√©dentes visites au resto. Z√©ro geste commercial, j'ai pay√© plein pot pour une formule mang√© √† moiti√©. Elle s'est juste contenter d'un "je suis d√©sol√©e" et le comble en partant elle me rappelle pour me faire la promo des r√©seaux sociaux du resto. Quelle √©norme maladresse üòÆ

Ps : j'ai attendu qques jours avant de poster ce message pour savoir si le resto allait me contacter pour se rattraper, mais RIEN.
Vous venez de perdre une habitu√©e. En un mois de pr√©sence dans la ville, cette mauvaise exp√©rience √©tait mon 3e passage et du coup mon dernier au Colibri.

Ps 2 : je viens de recevoir d'une ami, votre flyer de votre menu sp√©ciale aux saveurs d'Asie de jeudi 3 avril
textTranslated:
Last visit to the restaurant, a horror! I have breakfast and beforehand I had seen its composition. Already someone brings me a bottle of water with a damaged cap. I made the remark and the waitress was drunk to come back and get me another bottle. When I arrived there was no warm welcome and one of the waitresses only had eyes for her phone behind the bar...

They don't bring me any butter, or any venison without explanation. I get up to understand, they tell me ‚Äúwe can bring you some butter‚Äù no! It's not what I want, it's included in the formula... And as for venoisseries, I'm told that during Ramadan there aren't any. Explanation not clear at all. I point out to the waitress her unprofessional behavior, zero communication with the customer, I speak to her and she seems borderline casual, her tone rises a little.

I'm on the terrace and it was horrible. Too many flies and mosquitoes and no provisions in the restaurant to improve my comfort. I purposely didn't say anything and well, my comfort wasn't their problem.

They bring me an omelette, an orange cake (I hadn't asked for this extra cake), with honey and lab√© not included in the formula but the same zero explanation. The fruit salad was not fresh, the fruit was a little stale and there was a lot of water at the bottom of the dome

When paying, big disappointment from the manager with whom I had to communicate several times during my previous visits to the restaurant. Zero commercial gesture, I paid full price for a formula I ate half. She just said "I'm sorry" and to top it off, when she left, she called me back to promote the restaurant's social networks. What a huge clumsiness üòÆ

Ps: I waited a few days before posting this message to find out if the restaurant would contact me to make up for it, but NOTHING.
You just lost a regular. In a month of being in the city, this bad experience was my 3rd visit and therefore my last at the Colibri.

Ps 2: I have just received from a friend, your flyer for your special menu with Asian flavors for Thursday, April 3

textTranslated:
I ordered the kids menu for the children and I sincerely recommend it.
Composed of a mini burger, nuggets, fries, caprisun, yogurt drink, chocolate and toy, the children were delighted!
I also ordered an egg burger menu which was delicious, especially the sauce, lots of fries. Be careful, however, with the cooking of the steak which was a little black.
For dessert, the Dubai crepe was disappointing. Very large crepe for 2 or even 3 people but very thick resulting in a lack of filling for my taste. The Lotus dessert is not extraordinary, a lot of white ganache with no particular taste.
We took takeaway.
When children are happy, adults are less critical üòâ
I recommend for children's menus and burgers.
Ps: I struggled to find the menu in advance, especially for a large order or when you want delivery, so I'm sharing it with you here.
Enjoy your meal ü§ó

textTranslated:
Great seafood. Grilled fish and other seafood were so delicious that I went to Tafarit restaurant every evening. I didn't try the meat products but I think they were also delicious. It's definitely a flavor center that I only go to. No WiFi. No credit cards.

I noticed some changes during my May 31 visit. First of all, and unfortunately, the quality of the food has dropped a lot. Although I didn't order jumbo shrimp (Gambas), they brought small shrimp. The chef is very important in seafood restaurants. I don't know if the chef who does the grilling has changed. I hope the restaurant returns to its old days.

textTranslated:
Short information about grilled meat

Grilled, in Arabic cuisine, is anything that is grilled from sheep or lamb meat, preferably over charcoal. It is an Arabic word from the verb ‚Äúshwa‚Äù, and this dish is very popular in the Arab world and other countries such as Iran and Pakistan. All types of meat can be used for grilling, an example of which is Shish Tawouk (with chicken meat).

‚ÄúNouakchott restaurants with an Arabic flavour

The Mauritanian capital, Nouakchott, has become remarkably crowded with Arab restaurants, to the point that some have come to call it a phenomenon worthy of study. Reports indicate that 90% of the Arabs in Mauritania run restaurants and hotels that provide the people of Nouakchott with various Arabic flavors.

textTranslated:
A beautiful place and all the places are beautiful in this country, Chinguetti, or the beautiful country of Chinguetti, with its people, its land, the purity of its atmosphere, and the purity of its sea.
The painful observation is that you find beaches, wild places, and some parks neglected, and garbage here and there
Mauritania needs to pay attention to the environment and ensure the cleanliness of the place, our beloved ones. Preserve your home, for it is your country. Leave the place clean, and you will return to it again and again. Just as you found it clean, leave it clean for others.
And I remember you and myself
With a hadith of the Messenger, peace and blessings be upon him
Muslims are partners in three things: pastures, water, and fire.

textTranslated:
I liked the dishes that resemble alternative dishes for plant-based foods.

There are many delicious and healthy plant-based alternatives. Here are five of them:

1. **Tofu**: Made from condensed soy milk, it's a good substitute for animal proteins in many dishes.
2. **Tempeh**: Made from fermented soybeans, it has a strong flavor and a wonderful texture that can be used in frying or grilling.
3. **Vegan Burgers**: Made from vegetables, grains, and beans, they offer a delicious alternative to traditional burgers.
4. **Plant-Based Milk**: These include almond, oat, and rice milks, and are excellent alternatives to cow's milk.
5. **Cashew Cheese**: Made from cashews, it gives a distinctive flavor and a wonderful creamy texture that's great for cooking or as a topping for baked goods.
text_en:
I liked the dishes that resemble alternative dishes for plant-based foods.

There are many delicious and healthy plant-based alternatives. Here are five of them:

1. **Tofu**: Made from condensed soy milk, it's a good substitute for animal proteins in many dishes.
2. **Tempeh**: Made from fermented soybeans, it has a strong flavor and a wonderful texture that can be used in frying or grilling.
3. **Vegan Burgers**: Made from vegetables, grains, and beans, they offer a delicious alternative to traditional burgers.
4. **Plant-Based Milk**: These include almond, oat, and rice milks, and are excellent alternatives to cow's milk.
5. **Cashew Cheese**: Made from cashews, it gives a distinctive flavor and a wonderful creamy texture that's great for cooking or as a topping for baked goods.

name: Ammo The Reviewer
text:
The Tent Restaurant (Al-Khaimah) in Nouakchott is an establishment you should avoid like the plague. If you have even a shred of regard for your time, steer clear of this place. Our experience was nothing short of a nightmare.

After waiting for an hour for our food, we were informed that they didn't have what we ordered. Fine, mistakes happen, right? Wrong. After changing our order, they returned ten minutes later to inform us that they didn't have that either, but miraculously had the original order available now. Unbelievable.

To compound the frustration, our drink orders were repeatedly botched. Despite multiple attempts to rectify the situation, they consistently brought the wrong drinks. When we finally managed to catch their attention, we were met with an aggressive, rude, and shockingly racist manager. Their behavior was utterly disgraceful, and they even went as far as to hurl insults and demand we leave the premises.

As if that wasn't enough, when we dared to express our dissatisfaction, the manager threatened to call the police, accusing us of wasting their money despite our honest attempts to rectify their mistakes. It was a complete circus, and the final straw was when the manager tried to twist the situation, claiming that we had sworn at them and called them names, which was entirely false. They even had the audacity to tell us, "Go back to your country and order the juice there. This is Mauritania and this is how we make the juice."

In summary, The Tent Restaurant is a cesspool of incompetence, disrespect, and racism. Save yourself the trouble and dine elsewhere.

The Mauritanian capital, Nouakchott, has become remarkably crowded with Arab restaurants, to the point that some have come to call it a phenomenon worthy of study. Reports indicate that 90% of the Arabs in Mauritania run restaurants and hotels that provide the people of Nouakchott with various Arabic flavors.
